The government wants to limit the torture of "witches", they've published a pamphlet
Women who are declared witches in Burkina Faso have several characteristics in common.
They are more of an older generation, unable to work for health reasons, for example, and are single and childless.
The one who becomes a witch is sent to isolation so she doesn't endanger the rest of the village.
"A man's fate is very rare".
"Young, healthy women are not left behind because they help out with work and childbirth", says a nun who cares for more than a hundred women who have been expelled from their community in a special home in the capital of the West African state of Burkina Faso.
The local government has now decided to take action against an unusual "social measure".
She's published an information pamphlet to help curb the witch hunt.
There's a catch.
"More than 70 percent of Burkina Faso's adults are illiterate", notes the newspaper Die Standard, pointing to the disadvantage of literacy.
Accusations of witchcraft are common in other African lands.
In neighbouring Ghana, Ammy Hemmah, 72, died last week after being tortured, sprayed with kerosene and set on fire by three women and two men.
The BBC server reported the case.
The perpetrators claim it was an unfortunate coincidence.
According to their version, the woman was set on fire by the oil used for ritual anointing.
It was said to have been set on fire after a group tried to "exorcise an evil spirit" from a woman.
The isolation of "witches" is supported by people regardless of their level of education.
Der Standard quoted a 42-year-old businessman from Burkina Faso as saying: "Soul eaters have always been a danger", he said.
While the government in Burkina Faso is trying to quell the witch hunt, in The Gambia, the president himself participated in it last year.
"The Gambian president, Jammie, after the death of his aunt, launched a massive witch hunt allegedly to help her death and to try to use black magic to kill the president himself".
"He called in shamans from neighbouring Guinea, who, accompanied by police, soldiers and the president's personal security, forcibly escorted randomly selected men and women from Gambian villages to the president's farm in Kanilai", said Amnesty International in its report.
