The offices include a kindergarten, the architects understood.
The Avriopoint administrative building in Brno is the new headquarters of Arch.Design.
No one would expect him to also hide a miniature school with all the amenities - colorful walls, fancy furniture, a stack of toys, and even a miniature playground on the outdoor terrace.
Since October last year, it's been open to children of Arch.Design employees.
The architectural design company Arch.Design, from whose studios a number of important Brno buildings have emerged, has been planning space for its company mini-school since the first drawings of the Avriopoint building.
It employs almost 90 people, mostly in the baby boom era, and it was important to her that women designers and architects could get back to work quickly.
Along with the possibility of part-time work, the nursery is a benefit that Arch.Design offers to its employees as part of a social programme.
This allows builders and architects to combine the demanding work of caring for a child.
The mini-school was conceived by the employees of Arch.Design themselves and, with the support of the management, they managed to obtain a grant from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs.
The company mini-school is financed by the European Social Fund through the Operational Programme Human Resources and Employment and the Czech State Budget.
The grant funding (a grant of CZK 2.8 million) enabled them to purchase equipment and provide qualified staff and operations for two years.
After the financial subsidy is exhausted (2 years), Arch.Design is obliged to operate the mini-school at its own expense for 3 years.
The project took one year to prepare and was substantially assisted by Economy Rating in applying for a grant.
The care is provided by qualified staff, the children are cared for by a nurse and a primary school teacher, so children can attend kindergarten without age restrictions, but most are over 3 years old.
Since it is a "mini-school", only five children can be present at a time, but more children are taken in during the day.
The daycare is flexible according to the needs of the parents and the children of all employees have the same right to use the daycare regardless of the hierarchy of position in the company.
Although it is an individual education and care, the programme content in the mini-school is comparable to the framework curriculum of pre-school education.
Children not only play here, but they also receive a quality education - from basic knowledge to preparation for school, including English.
The classroom is equipped not only with toys and games but also with a computer for the children to use.
The presence of young children directly in the company creates a friendly and positive environment.
Parents can check on their child at any time and avoid stressful situations of late pick-up from preschools far from their parents' workplace.
This makes working time more productive for parents.
Not surprisingly, a naturally loyal employee-employer relationship develops here.
Arch.Design thus became one of the Czech companies that offer a significant benefit in recruiting new employees, are family-friendly and through this programme it has strengthened its personnel marketing.
The house of bones still fascinates after 100 years.
The roof looks like the back of a prehistoric lizard, the stairs resemble the spine of a dinosaur, and the balconies have open fish mouths.
This is the Casa Batlló in Barcelona by the Catalan architect Antoni Gaudí.
The organic shapes of the house have earned it the nickname "The House of Bones".
Organic shapes, wild colors, unusual use of stone, fragments of tiles and mosaics, a facade resembling scales and the ubiquitous soft curves, all are typical of Antoni Gaudí's Art Nouveau.
The façade of the house features dreamlike lines, soft colors, and textures reminiscent of nature and animals.
When you look closely, you can see geometry, rhythm, and a very thoughtful order.
At night, the entire facade of the house sounds even more dramatic, illuminated to enhance the glow of the colors.
The curvature and twisting of shapes is also found in the interior.
The wood in the waves mimics window frames, railings, door decorations, peepholes, and bars.
The Batlló House, located in the Eixample district at 43 Passeig de Gracia, a busy shopping street, was built by architect Emilio Sala Cortés.
The reconstruction took two years and the house was completed in 1906.
The investor, a wealthy industrialist named Josep Batlló, initially insisted on demolishing the old building and building a completely new one, but soon adopted Gaudí's idea of an unusual and cheaper reconstruction.
The Chinatown Casa Batlló, but Antoni Gaudi did not design it himself.
He was a collaborator of architect Josep Maria Jujol.
It was on his design board that the decorations for the representative apartment of the owner of the property and the use of mosaics on the facade were created.
A number of other creators and artists also worked on the facade.
Working together on the Casa Batlló house designs started a successful collaboration between Jujo and Gaudí.
Jujol was involved in the construction of Gaudí's Casa Milá and Güell Park, which houses other works by Gaudí.
Soon after its completion, the house earned the nickname "The House of Bones" from the locals because of its organic shapes.
Others have come to call it the "wiggling house" because of its specific window opening mechanism.
It is also said that the sword of Saint George, patron saint of Catalonia, is depicted on the top of the building.
Hidden religious motifs also include other sculptural features.
Gaudí designed a unique central heating system for the house, with vents and chimneys.
Strange as it may seem, their 45-degree slope.
Gaudí was totally disrespectful of the building codes of the day and was not bound by them.
Although he obtained a building permit from the city at the beginning of the project, the details he gave about the planned reconstruction were so vague that two years later, when the project was completed, the city council was appalled and demanded a repair.
For example, the council was concerned that the construction interfered with the pillars and the public sidewalk.
On the contrary, the correction never took place: just 15 days after the city asked for it, Josep Batlló applied for (and successfully obtained) a lease for the two highest floors of the building.
The owner himself moved into the lower floors.
The second floor gallery had a social room and the third floor had a bedroom and a private part of the apartment.
The ground floor was rented to a jewelry store.
The entire six-story house is traversed by a flight of stairs leading up to the roof terrace itself.
The basic elements of the reconstruction were the elimination of all right angles and straight lines and their replacement by curved walls.
Gaudí also worked with the modern concept of space connectivity.
The social area can be fully connected by opening the living room door and a larger company can communicate comfortably without losing the privacy needed for more intimate conversations.
The house with Gaudi's reconstruction has gained, in addition to the new facade, an unconventional roof and two additional floors.
Gaudí's play with light, blue and white glazed tiles that line the inner courtyard, and fireworks, too, is impressive.
The two-color play provides maximum light on all floors of the house.
All you had to do was bet on the principle that white reflects light more than dark, which absorbs sunlight.
The Casa Batlló, which was declared a Unesco World Heritage Site in 2005, is open to the public.
On the first floor of the house, the most spacious and luxurious apartment is open to the public.
The owners decided to do so in 2002, on the occasion of the 150th anniversary of the birth of the famous designer.
They continued the inspections, finding it a very profitable business, and extended the inspections to include common and attic areas, including the roof terrace.
The entrance fee is certainly not negligible, it is 16.50 euros and students, pensioners, groups and tourist card holders have a 20% discount.
The amount is far more than the price of admission to other Gaudí buildings in the city.
If you want to experience the true atmosphere of a dragon tower house, you must quickly befriend one of the tenants and visit him directly at home.
