More and more parents want tracking devices to keep tabs on their kids
Fear of their own child is leading more and more people to the idea of GPS babysitting.
The system, originally designed to track cars, can also track people's movements, helping in cases like the disappearance of nine-year-old Anicka Janatková.
The device is about the size of a matchbox, but soon it may be just as big as a watch.
Many people were frightened by the disappearance of Anicka and began to wonder how best to protect their children.
Even if it means violating their privacy.
"We try to tell everyone that this is not a spy operation, but another means to reduce the likelihood of a tragedy", says Petr Pilin of Macro Weil, a supplier of surveillance equipment to the Czech market.
"I admit that there are cases where such devices can be misused, such as when they are put in a bag by someone who does not know about it, but we have not seen such cases".
"Most of the time, customers actually buy it for security reasons", Pilin added.
He said that a child should always know what the "box" is for and how to use it in an emergency.
Child psychologist Dana Bochková points out that if a child does not want to wear something like this, he simply gets rid of it.
"Even very young children show great creativity in how to deliberately lose things when they don't want to be in control".
"Parents used to have high expectations for cell phones, but they can be turned off just like these surveillance devices", says Bočková.
It also disputes whether such a device would actually help in the event of an attack.
"In the case of an impending kidnapping, the perpetrator almost always ensures that the child has no electronics that could reveal his location".
"Now it's a phone".
"As surveillance devices become more widespread, they will also be sought out, "because their sales will be fueled by massive advertising".
"In this case, criminals are always one step ahead of the police", says a psychologist.
However, he admits that similar devices can help in the event of a sudden attack by a pedophile.
According to Robert Čech of RC Monitoring, a company that provides surveillance services for both cars and people, even if the surveillance device is destroyed immediately after an attack, its presence can help.
'The device can be set to periodically transmit a position after a certain time.'
"In the event of damage, at least the last known location of the person concerned shall be available".
"More expensive devices have built-in tiltometers, so that even if you slip and lie still, the device will send an immediate position warning", says Čech.
He says that a similar service can be provided by a smart phone with a navigation system, which can be accessed by downloading special software.
The problem with today's surveillance devices is that they are either devices the size of matchboxes or smaller cell phones.
They're always in danger of being lost.
According to Pilin of Macro Weil, this is why a device that looks like a regular digital watch is now being tested.
"The biggest advantage of this is that the attacker may not have to recognize the tracking device at all".
"Or it will only recognize them after a while and that can give the police extra time", he adds.
Whether the tracking devices evolve into bracelets or pendants, they'll still use the same technology used to monitor vehicles.
It is a combination of GPS (which uses standard car navigation) and a mobile phone function that reports the vehicle's current position.
The army has enough firepower to wrap around the Czech Republic, but it'll only last two years.
The Czech army has purchased 445 kilometers of explosive detonating ropes.
Last year, the Department of Defense delivered 224 kilometers of cable to the warehouse.
The army has enough for 225 years.
The problem is, the life of the cord is two, four years at the most.
The army bought the ignition cords from the STV Group, a.s. for 40 million crowns.
The General Staff, in justifying the purchase of such a large quantity of match cords, wrote that soldiers use 40 miles [60 km] of match cords a year in training.
However, the calculations of the army pyrotechnicians, which MF DNES addressed, show that then all generals, army command officers, secretaries or cleaners would have to undergo a very intensive pyrotechnic training every year.
The Minister of Defence, Alexander Vondra, and the Commander of the Armed Forces, Vlastimila Picka, are not excluded.
That alone would justify the army's annual consumption of 40 miles of matches.
That's the equivalent of 25,000 explosions.
