Longer index finger than ring finger means lower risk of cancer
Men who have a finger longer than the ring finger have a lower risk of prostate cancer.
That's the startling conclusion of a study published Wednesday in the British Journal of Cancer.
It could be related to the levels of the male hormone testosterone.
"Our results show that relative finger length can serve as a simple test of prostate cancer risk, especially for men under 60", says study co-author Ros Eeles, a professor at the Institute of Cancer Research at the University of Warwick.
The finger could help determine which men should be tested for prostate cancer, especially in combination with genetic risk or other risk factors, such as family health burden, Eeles added.
Between 1994 and 2009, she and colleagues in Britain followed more than 1,500 prostate cancer patients and over 3,000 healthy men at the same time.
More than half of the study participants had a finger on their right hand that was shorter than a ring finger.
They were as likely to get prostate cancer as 19 percent of those with the same finger length.
But for those with longer fingers than rings, the risk dropped by 33 percent, and for men by age 60, it dropped by 87 percent.
The ratio of the lengths of the two fingers - formed during the prenatal period - apparently reflects the different levels of sex hormones that the baby is exposed to in the womb.
Less testosterone is consistent with a longer index finger.
Previous research has shown that testosterone is what promotes the growth of prostate cancer.
A leading Czech geneticist and former president of the Czech Academy of Sciences, Professor Václav Pačes, told ČTK that he was only briefly aware of the study but that he did not think the link between finger length and cancer was "fully proven".
