Support for democracy in Latin America is growing, as is support for private enterprise.
Criminal activity is a bigger concern than unemployment.
And Brazil is considered by many regions to be more influential than the United States.
These are some of the findings of a recent Latinobarometer survey of 18 countries published exclusively in The Economist magazine.
Since the survey has been carried out regularly since 1995, it can monitor changes in attitudes across the region.
In this year's survey, which was conducted in September and early October, two related things dominate.
The first is that Latin America has a pretty cheerful mood.
The second is to increase the stability of attitudes towards democracy and its key institutions.
Support for democracy has increased significantly in several countries on the Pacific Rim of South America (see Table 1).
For example, in Peru, where economic growth has averaged 6% a year since 2002, support for democracy has risen from a low of 40% in 2005 to 61% this year.
It also rose in Mexico, where the economy was recovering from a deep decline in production last year.
But only about half of respondents in Mexico and Brazil, the two most populous regions, are of Democratic belief, which is below the regional average (see Chart 2).
Some 44% of respondents across the region expressed satisfaction with the way democracy operates in practice in their country, the same as last year but a large increase compared with 25% in 2001 (Graph 3).
Some 34% said they trusted the parliament in their country and 45% trusted the government, again the same figures as last year but a big difference compared to 2003 (17% and 24%).
Ten years ago, democracy in Latin America was undermined by the economic crisis.
Support arose during the global financial crisis, probably because many Latin American countries had only suffered a brief recession and were enjoying a strong recovery.
In addition, a stronger social safety net helped to protect the poor.
(The United Nations Economic Commission for Latin America reported this week that the proportion of Latin Americans living in poverty increased only slightly in 2009 and fell again to 32% this year.)
However, mood varies widely from country to country (see Chart 4).
Brazil's strong economic performance and the popularity of its outgoing president, Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva, are reflected in a widely accepted sense of progress.
This is more rare in Mexico and Central America, where the recession has been more severe and violent crime has worsened.
For only the second time since surveys began, more respondents across Latin America see crime rather than unemployment as the most important problem (see Chart 5).
About 31% say that they or their close relatives were victims of crime last year, but this is down from 38% last year and also the lowest number since 1995.
The stronger economic performance is reflected in the growing support for private enterprise and the market economy: around 71% of respondents across the region say that private enterprise is essential for development, up from 56% in 2007 (see Chart 6).
Some 58% agree that a market economy is the only system that will enable their country to develop, up from 47% last year.
Interestingly, 62% of respondents in Venezuela share this view (and 80% support private enterprise there), even though their leftist president Hugo Chávez is expropriating many private companies.
Brazil is the country that has the leading position in the field, as mentioned by 19% of respondents (compared to 18% last year), followed by the United States (9%, unchanged from last year) and Venezuela (9%, compared to 11% last year)
However, the United States is considered the most influential country of respondents in Mexico and much of Central America, with Venezuela enjoying success in Ecuador, the Dominican Republic and Nicaragua.
