Arsenic-resistant microbes raise the possibility of new life forms on Earth or elsewhere
The discovery of a strange bacterium that can use arsenic as one of its nutrients opens the door to the search for new life forms on Earth and perhaps beyond.
Researchers have discovered an unusual bacterium here on Earth, and they say it's a sign that life has possibilities beyond the basic elements that have been considered so far.
"This organism has a dual capacity".
"It can grow either with phosphorus or arsenic".
"This is very strange, but it is not proof that it is a form of truly 'alien' life", commented Paul C. W. Davies of Arizona State University, co-author of a report that appeared Thursday in the online edition of the journal Science.
For a long time, six basic elements - carbon, hydrogen, nitrogen, oxygen, phosphorus, and sulfur - were considered essential for life.
However, scientists have found that bacteria found in Mono Lake, California, are able to continue growing after arsenic is replaced by phosphorus.
"You start to wonder what else is possible", said Ariel D. Anbar of Arizona State University, co-author of the report.
This finding is important for the search for life beyond Earth because researchers need to be able to recognize life and know what life might look like, Anbar said.
The study focuses on microbes found on Earth.
However, a report about the discovery, published to discuss it, without revealing the details of the find, has sparked widespread speculation on the Internet that the report reveals the discovery of alien life.
It's not like that.
The discovery "shows that other planetary organisms may be able to use other elements to drive biochemistry and that the set of elements we consider 'standard' may not be so absolutely necessary for life", explained Charles Cockell, a professor at the Planetary and Space Sciences Research Institute, Open University, Milton Keynes, U.K.
Cockell wasn't part of the research team.
"This work is unusual because it shows the replacement of one element by another in basic biochemistry and biochemical structure", Cockell added.
It wasn't a random find.
Felisa Wolfe-Simon of NASA's Astrobiology Institute, who led the study, focused on Mono Lake because it has high levels of arsenic.
Arsenic and phosphorus are chemically very similar elements, so she reasoned that a microbe exposed to both elements might be able to substitute for one.
"Arsenic is toxic mainly because its chemical behavior is very similar to phosphorus".
"As a result, it is very difficult for organisms to separate these elements".
"However, arsenic is so different that it does not function as phosphorus does, and once it enters the body, it starts to work in biochemical processes", Anbar explained.
Scientists collect bacteria known as GFAJ-1 and expose them to increasing concentrations of arsenic, which allows the bacteria to adapt and grow.
Microbes grow better under the influence of phosphorus, but since they can also survive with the substitution of arsenic, it increases the possibility that a life form that uses arsenic could occur naturally, either elsewhere on Earth or on another planet or moon where arsenic is more common.
Jamie S. Foster, an assistant professor of microbiology at the University of Florida, said that the idea of arsenic being replaced by phosphorus is not new, but there has never been an example to prove this.
Arsenic was more common in earlier times on Earth, she said, so scientists speculated it might have been used by earlier life forms.
"This suggests that there may have been other ways of creating life, not just the way it formed in the early Earth", said Foster, who was not part of the Wolfe-Simon research team.
The research was supported by NASA, the Department of Energy and the National Institutes of Health.
