The prosecutors will not indict Senator Ensign
Justice Department prosecutors have cleared Senator John Ensign of criminal charges related to his affair with a former campaign adviser and his efforts to secure lobbying, the senator's lawyers announced Wednesday.
The decision ends the most serious legal threat faced by Mr. Ensign, a Nevada Republican who, until the scandal, was considered a possible Republican presidential candidate for 2012, whose affair made national headlines and damaged his career.
Mr. Ensign's office said it was "very pleased" with the decision, which followed an almost year-long investigation.
The senator could still face disciplinary action from the Senate Ethics Committee.
Mr. Ensign's lawyers said the Justice Department "has informed us that Senator Ensign will no longer be the subject of the investigation and that it has no plans to bring any further charges against him in this matter".
The Justice Department declined to comment on the case.
The decision came as a surprise to many ethics lawyers outside the Justice Department, who argued that there was strong evidence that Mr. Ensign was preparing to violate the federal lobbying ban.
Interviews, emails and other documents that were published in October 2009 in the New York Times said that Mr. Ensign helped Douglas Hampton, one of his assistants, secure lucrative lobbying to silence Mr. Hampton and his wife, Cynthia, about the senator's affair with her.
Mrs. Hampton used to work as treasurer for the Ensign campaign.
Mr. Ensign contacted a number of political supporters to find work for Mr. Hampton and to support their views after Mr. Hampton was hired to lobby for them, according to documents and interviews.
Because Hampton was until recently Mr. Ensign's assistant, he was legally barred from lobbying his former employer or the Senate for a year.
Ethics experts say the unusual settlement between Mr. Ensign and Mr. Hampton, who were friends before the affair, appeared to violate the prohibition against lobbying.
The evidence released "showed a clear case of a conspiracy to violate the law", said Stanley Brand, a Washington lawyer who specializes in defending clients under investigation by the government.
While Justice Department officials declined to explain the reasons for the decision in Senator Ensign's case, Mr. Brand and other lawyers specializing in ethics said the department is cautious about political lawsuits after a series of setbacks, including last year's decision to stay the case against former Senator Ted Stevens amid accusations of misconduct by the state attorney general.
Federal prosecutors "clearly hid guns", said Melanie Sloan, executive director of Citizens for Responsibility and Ethics in Washington, a law group that filed several complaints against Mr. Ensign in the case.
"It basically shows that high-ranking government officials are not subject to the laws", she added.
Paul Coggins, Mr. Ensign's lead attorney, said in an interview that he received a call from the DA on Monday and then the next day, telling him that the DA had found no charges against his client.
Mr. Ensign's defense team is working with the prosecution to convince them that the senator, as his office reiterated in a statement Wednesday, "acted in accordance with the law".
Mr. Coggins declined to elaborate on the legal arguments he submitted to the prosecutors.
"I'm not comfortable recounting the details of my discussions with the Justice Department except that we think they made the right decision", he said.
Last month, the Federal Election Commission decided to halt its investigation into a separate complaint in which an ethics group alleges that the payment of $96,000 by Ensign's parents to the Hamptons violated federal election law.
The Election Commission said they didn't have enough evidence to prove that the money was nothing more than a gift.
