Both sides want to find a way to protect some or all of them, permanently or temporarily.
Like the likely compromise on unemployment benefits only because Republicans can't watch as they support tax cuts for the wealthy while denying unemployment benefits to the unemployed.
After Tuesday's White House meeting, there is already more optimism about a possible agreement on these issues, along with the ratification of a new inaugural treaty.
But William Galston of the Brookings Institution warns that successful cooperation on critical issues will not necessarily lead to a two-party relationship when the 112th Congress convenes in January.
Rather, it is a likely period of disagreement, or even inevitable, he said.
"After the things that need to be done are done, psychology in the short term goes back to one of the confrontations", he said.
Wehner also expressed skepticism - which is widespread - that courtesy would lead to real cooperation.
"I look at everything that happens between now and 2012 as a shadow box where the main events will happen in 2012", he said.
