Co-Chairs Alan Simpson and Erskine Bowles have taken on one of the toughest jobs in Washington and are, in their view, putting the pressure on the deficit agenda in ways that cannot be ignored.
But they need 14 votes in the 18-member committee to make their plan official and fight to get as close to that number as possible.
The biggest resistance is among elected officials on the jury who suggest that when it comes to financial issues, we have, at least for today, little basis or will to compromise.
Galston predicts two phases in the battle between the White House and congressional Republicans.
The first begins next year in the form of partisan conflicts, when Republicans challenge Obama on budget, taxes and health care, followed by a period of greater partisan cooperation.
What's causing the shift?
