The software suggests improvements in vehicles in real time.
Since Red Bull entered Formula One in 2004, its history in this extraordinary world of speed has been one of surprise and success.
At first, no one took the newcomer's potential too seriously, and despite the recent upward trend, everyone was betting on Fernando Alonso's Ferrari triumph.
Without wanting to diminish the riding skills of the champion, the German Sebastian Vettel, or the capabilities of the Renault engine that drives his car, a legend was born in the world of Formula One - the "secret weapon" that multinational Siemens put in the hands of Red Bull to make it a winning team.
In fact, it is a powerful walking simulation software that was launched by a German company in 2007 for very long-distance motorsport purposes.
So called PLM, this powerful software tool, has been used to design assembly lines in manufacturing plants around the world, in power plants and for high-precision instruments.
The aim is to reproduce the product or process faithfully before it is actually created, thus avoiding unnecessary errors and costs.
PLM has facilitated the development of the Canon camera, Sukhoi aircraft and Nissan's most famous commercial vehicles.
Siegfried Russwurm, head of Siemens' industrial division, explains that the use of this software tool allowed the Red Bull team to make modifications and improvements that would otherwise be detected during races and tests "in a matter of hours, in near real time".
Russwurm says that in 1992 the stables had an average of 10 technicians who were able to perform a maximum of three or four refinements in a period.
Red Bull's team today has 180 highly skilled young professionals equipped with powerful information technology, who analyse and design every type of race car modification.
The Siemens executive explained that the PLM software is capable of analysing and improving all the elements of Red Bull racing cars except the engine, for which Renault is fully responsible.
The materials, fuel, aerodynamics and safety features are modified.
Changes can be made from virtual reality to reality in less than 24 hours thanks to advanced laser manufacturing systems and highly technologically advanced autoclaves.
