How do we interpret these movements?
Let me say in advance that Merkel's position is not a flaw in her communications policy.
On the contrary, it is another point in the complex process of redefining the euro.
And here Germany has a radically new vision of what its future should be, which is a collision with the idea of keeping to old traditions that is held by a large part of the other members.
Faced with European resistance, Germany is beginning to speculate on three possible ways out of the crisis.
The first is a strong euro area, including Germany, but also Austria and the Netherlands, while the southern countries would leave the euro area.
The second is the return to the brand - although it may now seem like scifi, this version has broad public support, approaching 50% of the population.
The third option is, according to German proposals, a restructuring of the euro with more macroeconomic supervision, budgetary tightening, penalties for guilty states, possible deferral of payments for some of them, and the possible extension of the cost of regulation to the private sector.
The German position is clear and has been defined for some time, so there is no room for twisting now.
First, when the International Monetary Fund and the European Commission encouraged deficits in 2009, the German government pulled out of the sleeve a constitutional reform to prevent them from 2016.
This was the first sign of a conflict between what Germany considered to be the right thing to do (fiscal austerity and fiscal stability plans) and what its European partners, including France, were doing.
The other was shown by this Central European country, as Merkel painfully delayed the decision to rescue Greece.
It was already the subject of sharp criticism at the time, but the truth is that the political consensus in Germany and the public opinion that was also published were strongly against the rescue of Greece.
Finally, in the last days of October, Merkel again made a clear statement when she demanded that the European Union's conventions be reformed to allow a rescue of a Member State and at the same time to oblige private creditors to bear part of the costs.
This position was interpreted as anti-European, as it hastened the Irish crisis and everything else.
However, its proposal, albeit in a somewhat moderate form, was approved and we should be following the Union reform process in the coming months, which should allow for these measures from 2013.
Germany has drawn a red line that it will not cross.
And he is telling us all that, although measures are now needed which he seems to disagree with, the old way of working of the euro will be over on that date.
The year 2013 will mark the birth of a new monetary zone, in which countries that break the rules will be severely sanctioned and may be forced to declare a moratorium on payments, and the private sector will also have to bear some of the costs.
Germany is suggesting that we must take a strict growth path with higher savings and investment rates, moderate consumption, improved productivity and competitiveness, and capital reserves.
Another option based on debt and construction, with huge balance of payments gaps, as prevailed during Spain's boom years, they simply will not tolerate.
The offer is clear.
And we would be making a mistake not to understand that.
It is not just a question of restoring the government deficit to 3% in 2013.
What they want from us is much harder.
And the worst part is, under these conditions, we could be wrong.
I hope this current turbulence will be replaced by more calm.
And that we will seize the opportunity they're giving us in the spring of 2013.
Prime Minister Zapatero seems to have understood this too, and his two statements (reforms promised after meeting with big business last Saturday and yesterday's announcement of new measures) suggest that despite criticism of Merkel, the path to the idea of making things right has opened up.
But the red line that Germany has drawn is here, and it doesn't seem to want to move with it.
And among the options to be considered, leaving the eurozone full of not-so-serious countries cannot be ruled out.
Well, Germany will always be able to tell us that they warned us.
Sports and circumvention
The finesse that Alonso and Ramos showed in the match against Ajax shows ingenuity, not the intention to escape punishment.
The alleged suspension of two Real Madrid players (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramos) from the November 23 Champions League match against Ajax has caused a sea of ink to be written on whether or not this is unsportsmanlike behaviour and whether UEFA should eventually punish both players.
It is known that, a few minutes before the end of the match (which their team had clearly won), the named players, one after the other, deliberately wasted time during the foul-playing period in order to provoke the referee, who showed them the second yellow card.
In this way, both players will fulfil their prescribed penalty in the next match against Auxerre - with Real Madrid finishing top of their group - and will be able to proceed to the next stage, stripped of their cards.
Eventually, the UEFA disciplinary committee handed coach Jose Mourinho a two-match ban and the guilty players were fined.
Provoking a yellow card under similar circumstances is not a new practice, but more or less common in football.
It's so widespread that it's part of the ethos of football, the rules that are not written, but they are followed.
Part of the debate in this case was caused by the fact that the Real Madrid team (which boasts of its nobility and honor in its anthem, and which has already fined its players for similar acts) was involved, and it seems that the dramatization led by Mourinho adds another episode to his long history of comedian and provocateur.
In any event, the debate revolves around whether this type of behaviour, which is not expressly prohibited by the rules, is contrary to the principles of sport, that is, whether these acts circumvent the law; it is indeed an action respecting the rules of sport, the meaning of which, however, seems to be being circumvented.
The type of damage such conduct causes to the sporting spirit is being addressed.
One of the requirements of sportsmanship is the physical inviolability of the opponents, which in these cases has not been violated, i.e. no violent play has taken place.
Another aspect of fair play is to avoid giving players an advantage over the opposing team by their foul - which is not the case here.
So the paradox of the Real Madrid players' actions is that there was no trick or circumvention, no hidden violation of the rules to avoid a penalty, but rather that the behavior was as obvious as possible in order to get a penalty.
They waited and were happy to be punished.
Another question, though, is what advantage will the guilty have from their willful transgression?
It must be noted that the opponent is not put at a disadvantage and that no advantage is gained in the current match, as the obvious consequence is that the team itself will have fewer players.
And it's not a useful strategy for the next game, either, because the club won't be able to count on these players.
The advantage is obviously that players start the next phase of the Champions League without cards that could jeopardize their participation in the next match.
However, this is an advantage in the long run and with a certain degree of uncertainty, so at first glance the team may be eliminated, and besides this action will get the players off the penalty and move on to the second round of cards, where one card less is needed to be eliminated than in the first round.
So as the rounds continue, it won't be entirely clear if this is an advantage.
In short, these negotiations are not against the spirit of sport, which is to make strategic decisions that allow you to get the maximum benefit within the rules.
In the case we're dealing with here, the players didn't aim to avoid the penalty (which would be a clear case of circumvention), but rather chose when to submit to it.
They made strategic decisions without avoiding or running from punishment.
Although the line between wit and circumvention is not entirely clear, I believe that in this case it was clearly wit.
I think the controversy arises for two reasons: because there were two self-exclusions and because of the way the instructions were passed from the leadership to provoke them.
The damage to sporting principles by these actions is not as much ethical as it is aesthetic.
