To complete the complication of the numbers, the calendar concentrated requests this year (when Christmas Day fell on a Friday) for the week of December 13, creating an avalanche of reservations for the peak days (16 and 17), while there was almost no traffic in the previous week.
As has been the case since 2008, when the lean years began, many companies have cancelled their collective parties for budgetary reasons.
To keep up the tradition, many employees pay for parties out of their own pockets.
Regardless of the situation, many are demanding prices that are within the limits of what is affordable, says Gaieta Farras, president of the Gremi de Restauració de Barcelona.
A representative of the board of restaurant establishments is not at this time daring to predict what the celebrations will be this month.
"People think twice before making a reservation".
"They want to get out, but they're cautious about the price", he adds.
Shops will do well for those "who offer quality and good service at a good price", he says, noting that the crisis has led to customers' tendency to go down a notch and that most customers now want to spend around 25 euros.
A survey of various facilities shows that the largest influx of booking requests is on the evening of December 17.
The Soteras Group reports a real boom in bookings for this Friday, with the most demands being for spending under 30 euros, which is accompanied by the menu offered, whose total prices are between 25 and 30 euros.
In addition, the number of early bookings in Andilana, another important company, which has 16 establishments in the city (Hostal de la Rita, Market, La Fonda and others), has brought the peculiarity of this year's calendar of more early bookings since the beginning of November.
"We have done everything possible to keep prices from last year, and our menu for everyone to choose from ranges from 19.95 to 30 euros", they say.
The AN Grup group, which includes El Mussol, Attic and QuQu and a total of 23 companies, remains optimistic after recording an increase in profits since the second half of the year and has a relatively solid outlook for Christmas sales.
Sources at the company say December 18 will be a busy day as well, with a Christmas Eve party among friends.
The new menu, which is based on the Christmas menu, has been added to its six group menus, with a budget of €30 or more, as it has seen a 10% increase in the trend of visitors spending compared to last year in exchange for other items such as cava.
They also noted that companies are already appearing to invite their employees back, and the size of the groups seems to be slightly larger.
Vice-president of Fecasarm (which includes institutions such as the Barcelona Bar, Restaurant and Leisure Centre Association) Enric Goma believes he is beginning to see the end of the tunnel and says bookings have "revived" although customers are "buying to the max".
This impression has not diminished during the Christmas celebrations, no matter who pays, he points out.
Pakistan's nuclear program has caused great unrest in the United States.
Islamabad is producing nuclear weapons "at a faster rate than any other country".
Wikileaks documents confirm ties between the Taliban and Pakistan.
The content of the correspondence between the US Embassy in Pakistan and the US State Department published by WikiLeaks confirms the extraordinary unease that Pakistan's nuclear program is causing in Washington.
In addition to providing illuminating and significant details about the content of the communications and thoughts of the representatives of the North American diplomacy in Islamabad, the documents reveal that cooperation between the two countries on nuclear security is "in decline" rather than increasing, and that the unstable Asian country produces "more nuclear weapons than any other state".
The peculiarity of Pakistan's nuclear program - that its weapons are not disassembled but are stored in pieces to make them easier to destroy in the event of an attack - is one of the main reasons for Washington's vigilance.
This is what Ambassador to Pakistan Anne W. Patterson calculated in a report before the visit of then-National Security Advisor James Jones: "The proximity of some nuclear facilities to Taliban-controlled territory, the alleged dispersal of nuclear material, and the vulnerability of transportation of nuclear material".
The increased number of people associated with nuclear arsenals and the guided missile program is no longer seen only by the United States but also by Russia as a growing and cause for alarm.
"Pakistan has had to hire personnel with strict religious beliefs to protect its nuclear facilities; the decline in education and culture has given extremist organizations more opportunities to recruit people to work in nuclear or missile programs", said Yuri Korolev, a Russian foreign ministry expert, at a meeting with his U.S. counterparts.
The biggest news document released by Julian Assange's server is the declining cooperation between the US and Pakistan on nuclear proliferation issues and the increased pace of Pakistani production of these weapons.
A cable issued by the embassy in May, describing communication with Pakistan as "frustrating", states: "Transparency often lacks; offers of help remain unanswered or are rejected".
In another report, Peter Lavoy, a national intelligence officer for South Asia, notes that "despite the economic disaster, Pakistan is building nuclear weapons at a rate no other country in the world has".
Ambassador Petterson also asks Washington to "make it very clear" during the visit of Army Chief General Ashfaq Kayani that "the Pakistani military must end its silent support for terrorist groups".
The hunt for the head of WikiLeaks
Obama is appointing a senior counterterrorism official to prevent further leaks.
Interpol is issuing a "red notice" to track down and determine where Assange might be.
Everything about WikiLeaks and its founder Julian Assange is a complicated maze where it's hard to be sure of the facts.
Interpol issued an "emergency call", called a red notice, yesterday to "locate and track the movement" of Assange.
But this is not a classic warrant for your arrest.
Besides, this challenge is not new, but dates back to November 20th.
And it has nothing to do with the recent leak of over a quarter of a million diplomatic documents, but with the sexual abuse allegations the Australian faces in Sweden.
In addition, WikiLeaks founder Mark Stephens' lawyer assures us that "the police know where and how to contact Mr. Assange".
It was November 20th when the International Police Corps based in Lyon, France issued this order at the request of Sweden, but did not publish it until yesterday when it received permission from the Swedish authorities.
In this situation, 188 countries have Interpol's instructions to identify or locate Assange "with a view to temporarily detain and extradite him".
Although Interpol cannot order the arrest of a person who is the subject of a red notice, many Member States, the organisation explained, regard red notices as allowing for the arrest to be carried out - this must be ensured by the national police - especially where States have a bilateral extradition agreement, as in the case of Sweden and England, where Assange is presumably to be held.
This move was scandalized by Assange's lawyers, who yesterday published a letter claiming that the 39-year-old WikiLeaks founder was willing to answer questions from Swedish authorities via video conference.
They also recall that Assange requested and subsequently received permission to leave Sweden from the prosecutor of his case, who they compare to the legendary Lavrentii Pavlovich Beria, head of Stalin's security.
"This is a hunt, not a legal pursuit", the letter states.
While the world is searching for him - and his mother in Australia is defending her son's innocence - Assange remains in the dark, but he is not silent.
On Monday, he gave a Skype interview from an unknown location to the editor of Time magazine, in which he demanded the resignation of U.S. Secretary of State Hillary Clinton.
"If she turns out to be responsible for ordering US diplomats to conduct espionage at the UN in violation of international conventions to which the US is a signatory, she should step down", he said.
His opinion was rejected yesterday by White House press secretary Robert Gibbs, who called his demand for his resignation "ridiculous and absurd".
"I'm not entirely sure why we should care about the opinion of the individual who runs the website", he told CNN.
Obama himself has commissioned a senior official in charge of counterterrorism, Russell Travers, to prevent further leaks.
President Barack Obama's intention to stop giving Assange more prominence contrasts with the views being proclaimed by conservative politicians and commentators these days.
Peter King, a congressman who will chair the House Homeland Security Committee in January, has asked the State Department to consider listing WikiLeaks as a terrorist organization "so that anyone who provides financial or other assistance can be targeted and prosecuted".
Tom Flanagan, an adviser to Canadian Prime Minister Stephen Harper, went further, declaring that Assange should "be killed", which he had to withdraw.
"Obama should put a reward on him or use a drone or something".
The one who didn't apologize was Mike Huckabee, a Baptist minister, former governor of Arkansas and a possible presidential candidate.
"Whoever is in government, whoever is responsible for the leak of information, has committed treason and any punishment other than death would be too lenient", he told Fox News.
