The United States is changing its visa rules
People will have to contact the Visa Applicant Services Centre before the interview at the Consular Section; the cost will be lower and the waiting time will be shorter.
As of January 10, 2011, the visa processing process at U.S. Embassies and Consulates will change.
The new procedure will require most applicants to contact the Visa Applicant Services Centre (ASC) before the interview at the Consular Section.
ASC personnel will collect the applicant's biometric information and it will be evaluated by the Consular Section prior to the interview.
The new procedure will have certain advantages, including the following:
The total cost of visa processing will be lower, no more fees for arranging an appointment, one for processing an application and another for the delivery of a document by a transport service.
The applicant shall pay only one fee covering all three services.
The current tariff remains unchanged: the equivalent of $140 for a tourist visa, $150 for visa applications (including temporary workers' visas) and $390 for business and investor visas.
People who wish to renew their visas will not have to go through an interview with a consular officer, but simply go to the nearest ASC, where they will present their documents and have their fingerprints taken.
Since biometrics will be collected at the ASC, applicants who require a second interview at the Consular Section will spend less time here than in the past.
Similarly, those applying for visas at the consulates in Ciudad Juárez, Monterrey, and Nuevo Laredo will no longer have to pay an extra $26 service fee.
The visa application procedure for the United States of America is currently being implemented in the United States.
