The discovery could support the theory that there are other creatures besides us living in inhospitable conditions that were once considered uninhabitable, and that they might one day become intelligent creatures like humans if their conditions are improved.
It appears to be a microbe found at the bottom of Mono Lake in Yosemite National Park, California, where it lives in an environment that was considered too toxic for any form of life because the lake is rich in arsenic.
The creature somehow uses arsenic to sustain life, and it's this ability that makes it more likely that life like this could exist on other planets that don't have an atmosphere like Earth's.
According to astrobiologists, if these organisms use arsenic in their metabolism, it will prove that "there is another, different form of life than the one we know".
The space agency will announce the true impact of the findings at a press conference tomorrow.
The conference will feature geobiologist Pamela Conrad, who studies the possibility of life on Mars; biologist Steven Benner, one of the scientists who is studying Titan (Saturn's largest moon) with the prospect of its chemical composition being similar to Earth's.
