A Worldwide Plan to Restore Light
The UN yesterday proposed in Cancun a plan to restore home, business and industrial lighting in 100 countries to achieve a reduction in greenhouse gas (GHG) emissions equivalent to almost one-third of the additional reductions needed to stabilize the planet's climate between now and 2020.
This ambitious plan is part of the large-scale concrete projects that the UN wants to promote in Cancun to compensate for the lack of hard-to-implement reduction commitments by industrialised countries.
According to the plan presented yesterday, if the hot bulbs, which still monopolize 50 to 70 percent of the market, are replaced by fluorescent light bulbs, or better yet, LEDs, a substantial amount of the 1.8 billion tons of GHG emissions on the planet from lighting would be decomposed.
Lighting is responsible for 8% of global emissions.
That's equivalent to 70% of the emissions from the entire car fleet on the planet.
In Copenhagen last year, major emitters such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, joined voluntary reduction plans that should allow global GHG emissions to fall from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
But we need to subtract another 5 Gt from this balance to stabilize global warming to 2 degrees Celsius by 2020 to prevent it from getting out of control.
In light bulbs, 95% of the energy is dissipated as heat and the remaining 5% is the product of light.
With fluorescent light bulbs, we reduce energy consumption by 75%, and with the new LED light bulbs, we reduce energy consumption by half.
Fluorescent light bulbs last on average between 6,000 and 10,000 hours.
The new LED bulbs, introduced this week by Philips - which was reportedly involved in a UN study - have an estimated lifespan of 25,000 hours and use 80% less energy than a light bulb, giving us an idea of the potential savings with a replacement plan that would be implemented in 100 countries.
All these new bulbs can also work with rheostats and emit less heat.
And they don't contain any mercury.
Several experts have expressed reservations about fluorescent bulbs because they contain mercury and need to be classified as hazardous waste, which is still not possible in developing countries unless manufacturers set up collection centres.
However, the report notes, the planet's main source of mercury emissions is not a fluorescent bulb but rather coal-fired power plants, which release much of the mercury needed to produce electricity wasted in hot bulbs.
In the United States alone, these plants put 25,000 tons of mercury into circulation each year.
The report also details the benefits that each country would derive from this international programme.
For example, Indonesia would save a billion dollars a year in electricity and eight million tons of CO2, which is the equivalent of 3.5 thermal power plants that cost 2.5 billion to build.
