Snow and avalanches: 24 counties are on orange alert.
The snowfall continues to cause difficulties for transport, especially on secondary roads in Brittany, and there is a risk that it will disrupt some economic activities.
Twenty-four counties are now on orange alert for snow and avalanche.
L'Eure, l'Eure-et-Loir, les Deux-Sèvres and la Vienne, joined 20 districts that have already declared an orange alert, 18 as of Wednesday afternoon and two, la Dordogne and la Gironde, later in the night.
According to Météo France, heavy snowfall is causing problems in the north of Gironde and the Charentes and slight snowfall in Ile-de-France.
Snow cover of 2 to 5 cm, with places of 7 to 10 cm, is expected in the affected districts and cover of 1 to 3 cm, with places of up to 5 cm, in the Paris region.
The regions concerned are the Charente, Charente-Maritime, Côtes d'Armor, Finistère, Gironde, Dordogne, du Poitou and the regions of Basse-Normandie, Ile-de-France and Limousin.
The snowfall is large enough to cause traffic problems and disrupt some economic activities, forecasts Météo France.
On the Côtes d'Armor coast, some districts have banned heavy goods traffic - trucks over 7.5 tonnes on the Guingamp-Lannion and Saint-Brieuc-Loudéac routes.
Traffic on secondary roads in Brittany is very difficult, police say, and they recommend driving only if absolutely necessary, and some trucks have been cancelled for the day.
In Picardy, school parties are forbidden on Thursdays.
No special measures are foreseen to restrict freight traffic on Wednesday evening.
The district office "urges all motorists to exercise the utmost caution on the roads and to adapt their driving to the nature of the road".
The Directorate General of Civil Aviation (DGAC) asked airlines to cancel 25% of their flights at Paris' Roissy airport and 10% at Orly on Thursday due to expected snowfall.
The DGAC recommends that passengers using air transport services contact their airline.
In the United Kingdom, Gatwick Airport in south London and Edinburgh Airport in Scotland are closed until Thursday morning.
Metro Grand Paris: first financial proposals
Since the debate on the modernization of transport in Ile-de-France is in full swing, billions have been pouring down.
At least during the discussion.
We would like to mention in particular the 23 billion for the Grand Paris Metro, to be built by the Société du Grand Paris.
In order to enable this construction to start, the State announced a subsidy of EUR 4 billion.
In theory, this is an amount which would then allow SGP to use part of its dual source of funding for the contracts.
Today we finally get to the First Amendment.
The 2010 Finance Amendment Act, which is being considered by the National Assembly's Finance Committee this morning, contains mechanisms designed to secure these funds.
There are two: the creation of a special equipment tax and an increase in the tax on offices in Ile-de-France.
First, as we read in the text of the bill, Article 15 reads "in favour of the public institution Société du Grand Paris".
It is numbered: 'The yield on this interest is EUR 117 million per year'.
The second is the restructuring of the existing office fee 'to modernise it, to increase the revenue generated by it and to benefit Société du Grand Paris'.
How much would that be?
It's a vision.
It's not listed in the text.
We're a long way from 4 billion.
'It is specified that these fiscal resources are added to the EUR 4 billion of capital support to be mobilised by the State and invested in Société du Grand Paris under the project', reads the explanatory memorandum.
For us at SGP, this system is not shocking.
"Once we generate revenue, we can cover the study for three years and then dig up $4 billion", it explains.
"It will be included in the budget and used as needed".
SGP estimates that EUR 4 billion will be committed only in 2013 for the 2014 budget.
This mechanism, in which the promised 4 billion belong to subscribers who are not yet present, risks provoking a somewhat heated parliamentary debate.
The first public hearing will be on December 7th.
Vengeful hackers and disruptive spies
The WikiLeaks case has a double meaning.
On the one hand, there is a flagrant scandal, a scandal that seems to be a scandal only in the face of the hypocrisy that governs relations between states, citizens and the press.
On the other hand, it speaks of profound changes at the international level, and predicts a future of controlled regression.
But let's go in order.
The first aspect of WikiLeaks, is the fact that every document compiled by any intelligence agency, any nation, is made up entirely of press cuts.
The Americans' "extraordinary revelations" about Berlusconi's sex life are announcements that have been read for months in any newspaper (all but the two Berlusconi owns), and the disgustingly caricatured profile of Gaddafi has long been the subject of cabaret sketches.
The rule that secret documents must consist only of information already known is fundamental to the dynamics of intelligence, and not just in this century.
If you go to a bookstore that specializes in esoteric literature, you will find that each work (on the Grail, the Rennes-le-Château mystery, the Templars or the Masons) repeats exactly what has already been written in previous works.
Not only because the author of occult texts is reluctant to seek out new information (or know where to look for reports of nonexistent information) but because those who practice the occult only believe what they already know and confirm what they have already learned.
That's the mechanism of Dan Brown's success.
The same goes for classified documents.
The informant is lazy, and the lazy (or short-tempered) head of the secret service (and if he is not, he could be, as I know, the editor of the newspaper Libération) who only believes what he admits to be true.
The top secret information about Berlusconi that the U.S. Embassy sent to the State Department was the same as the one that Newsweek published a week earlier.
So why the fuss about these documents being revealed?
On the one hand, they say what every educated person already knows, which is that embassies, at least since the end of World War II, and since the heads of state can phone or fly off to dinner together, have lost their diplomatic function and, with the exception of a few small exercises in the national team, have been transformed into spy centers.
Any viewer of investigative films knows perfectly well that hypocrisy is the only way to seemingly ignore it.
However, the fact that it is being repeated in public dishonors the duty of hypocrisy and casts a bad light on American diplomacy.
Second, the idea that any hacker could gain access to the most highly classified information in the most powerful country in the world is a blow, not a minor one, to the prestige of this government department.
Scandal affects both victims and perpetrators.
But let's move on from that to the deep truth of what happened.
Once upon a time, in Orwell's time, it was possible to seize all power, like some Big Brother, controlling every move of his people.
Orwell's prophecy has been proven since the ability to control every move through the phone, every transaction made, hotel visited, highway used, and so on, has made the citizen a total victim of the crown of power.
But when we demonstrate, as we're doing now, that even the "tombs" of the most secret information of the powerful can't resist a hacker's attack, the control message stops being one-way and becomes circular.
Power is controlled by every citizen, but every citizen, or at least the hacker - elected as the citizen's avenger - can know all the secrets of power.
How can a power sustain itself if it can no longer keep its own secrets?
It is true that Georg Simmel said that the real secret is the empty secret (and the empty secret can never be revealed); it is also true that all information about the character of Berlusconi or Merkel is really a secret empty secret because it is pulled out of public life; but to reveal, as WikiLeaks did, that Hillary Clinton's secret was empty secrets is to strip him of all power.
WikiLeaks didn't make any mistakes with Sarkozy or Merkel, but it did something big with Clinton and Obama.
What will be the consequences of this blow to the power so great?
Clearly, in the future, states will not be able to send sensitive information online - it would be like putting it on a street corner poster.
But it is also quite clear that with current technology, it is useless to hope that a telephone message can be kept secret.
There's nothing easier than finding out if and when a head of state has been on a plane and contacted one of his colleagues.
How can private and sensitive information be kept secret in the future ?
I know that my forecast for the moment is science fiction and therefore fantastic, but I have to imagine government officials discreetly carrying out formalities on uncontrollable routes, carrying only the reports they know by heart or rather hiding precious information in the heel of their shoes.
The information will be kept in unique copies in keyed drawers: overall, the Watergate espionage attempt was less successful than WikiLeaks.
I had the opportunity to write that technology is now moving sideways forward, which means backwards.
A century after the wireless telegraph revolutionised communications, the Internet has rehabilitated the wire-based telegraph.
Video cassettes (analogue) allowed film lovers to shoot a film step by step, moving it back and forth and revealing all the secrets of editing, while now CDs (digital) only allow you to jump through chapters, i.e. through macropores.
By express train, we can get from Rome to Milan in three hours, whereas the flight and the transportation involved take three and a half hours.
It is not unusual, then, for politics and communications to return to horse-drawn carriages.
One last thing.
At other times, the press tried to understand what was going on inside the embassy.
Now it's the embassies that ask for confidential information from the press.
Climate: how France hacked its funding pledges
One year after the Copenhagen Accord, it is time to test the promises of rapidly unlocked financing (called fast start or early finance) made by developed countries.
And the great French hack was exposed
In the Copenhagen Accord, developed countries committed to provide $30 billion between 2010 and 2012.
The European Union has pledged €7.2 billion over three years and France €1.26 billion (or €420 million a year).
At the start of COP16, the EU took a big step to convince its partners of the reality of its commitment to fast start funding: a report detailing the action of its Member States, a press conference, a grand side event, a distribution of brochures...
Transparency operation invaluable and valued for its true value: developed countries and civil society would like all developed countries and civil society to treat them equally and with the same degree of accuracy.
The EU announces that it has committed €2.2 billion in 2010, putting it on track to deliver on its €7.2 billion pledge in 2012.
But if you look at the detail, you see that things are much more complicated.
These funds are 'new and additional' under the Copenhagen Accord to ensure that the increased burden is realised without prejudice to ODA.
Unfortunately, there is no agreement on what "new and additional" means.
While the European Commission proposed harmonisation, some Member States, including France, blocked the process.
Today, everyone chooses the reference that suits them best.
The European Commission, for example, took 2009 as the reference year: international funding was maintained and it is adding 150 million over three years under the fast start funding.
Other countries have chosen similar references with annual payment deadlines or with deadlines at the level of official development assistance.
By contrast, France considers that the funding of 'all new projects' in 2010 is 'new and additional'.
In other words,there is no reference to expenditure in previous periods or to the overall level of ODA.
In particular, the total amount of aid granted by France to developing countries may remain unchanged (or even decrease) and must comply with its commitment to finance 'new and additional ...'
Another crucial factor is the distribution of gifts and loans.
There's no rule yet, and everyone chooses their own way of calculating.
Some, like France, think that a euro borrowed is equal to a euro given.
Obviously, it's hard to prove: effort is not comparable.
If the use of loans can be justified for some investment that is profitable (often emissions reduction projects based on more efficient technologies), it is foolish to present one euro we receive as equivalent to one euro we give... , we should not understand it as a title to our liabilities but as a loan price to the creditor country (i.e. equivalent interest rate).
But France can only justify this: it 'fulfils' its commitment of €420 million, of which 91.5% is a loan (€389.8 million) and 8.5% is a donation (€36.1 million) - see the EU document to verify this for yourself.
It is the only country in the Union to use the loan on such a scale.
Germany has requested 46% of this, while Denmark, the Netherlands and Slovakia (among others) are meeting their commitments with 100% donations.
In other words, if the absolute majority of the European Union gives €1 to fulfil its promise, France gives only 10 cents and considers this effort comparable.
That's a beautiful piece of popcorn!
In conclusion, in its financing of the 'fast start', France operates with a double-track approach: on the one hand, with the development of the action over time and, on the other, with the real financial burden.
Although it spends only €36.1 million, it is able to convince the public that it is spending €420 million 'new and additional' in line with its promises.
Manipulation of the finance minister (because it seems that Bercy was the one who made the decision) could have a double negative impact, both inside the EU (why would member states continue to donate when they can only lend?) and in the negotiations, because developing countries are not completely naive...
The chapter on early finance is just a small question, relatively short-term, in relation to the series of climate discussions.
But she could be an extra grain of sand in a huge machine like the UNFCCC.
Let's hope that's not our case.
Whatever the case, it is essential to draw on the lessons of this first year of early funding.
France should first notify a change in its accounting practices for 2011 and 2012, in the spirit of respect for its obligations and fairness towards other countries of the European Union.
But above all, France should avoid the discussion on contributions to long-term financing (another crucial chapter currently under discussion): we do not avoid the question of 'additionality' or the way loans are accounted for.
France should change its attitude to become as progressive on these deposits as it is on others.
So everyone's hopes are in the new environment minister, Mrs. Kosciusko-Morizet, who's coming to Cancun next week.
The surprising announcement of France's fast start and its vision of 'additionality' and the use of loans could raise the level of international confidence necessary to move forward in the discussions.
A warning about pesticides that children swallow.
A ten-year-old child ingests 81 different chemicals in one day, according to a study published this Wednesday by the Future Generations Association (formerly the Movement for the Rights and Preservation of Future Generations).
The association, which notes that its results "have no statistical significance given the small number of samples analysed but are characteristic of the subject matter", bought food normally eaten in four meals and one light snack per child of about ten years old in supermarkets in L'Oise and Paris between July and September.
These typical foods, which include the official recommendations - five pieces of fresh fruit and vegetables, three dairy products and 1.5 litres of water a day - as well as sweets, have been analysed by research laboratories for chemicals, pesticides, heavy metals and other pollutants.
The balance sheet is staggering: 81 chemicals, 42 of which are classified as possible or probable carcinogens, and five substances are classified as clear carcinogens, as well as 37 substances that could act as disruptors of the endocrine glands (EPs), according to studies by several institutions, such as the International Cancer Research Center.
"While in almost all cases the legal limits for each chemical taken individually are not exceeded, our research clearly shows that the reality of consumer exposure to contaminants, possibly carcinogens, and/or PE is staggering", says the association.
Butter and milk tea for breakfast alone contain about ten residues with possible carcinogenic effects and three that have been shown to be certain carcinogens, as do about 20 residues that could disrupt the hormonal system.
An apple imported from Brazil, described in the study as a small snack, contains traces of six chemicals, including a fungicide banned in France.
The same is true for Kenyan green beans, which are included in the lunch, and in which the study found traces of potent insecticides banned in the EU.
In addition, minced meat steaks, canned tuna, and even goose and gum were peppered with pesticides and other chemicals.
The tap water analysis revealed the presence of nitrates and chloroform.
The salmon steak for dinner was the "richest" with 34 chemical residues found, and even the analysis of a plastic plate used to heat food in a microwave did not escape analysis.
The ultimate risk to consumers of this 'cocktail of contaminants' is probably underestimated,' the study concludes.
The Ecological Europe-Green (EE-LV) has proposed a moratorium on pesticide use to halt the "rise in civilization diseases" "in the face of an urgent situation".
In July, a study by the European Food Safety Authority (EFSA) examined the presence of residues of 365 different pesticides identified in fruit and vegetables consumed in Europe, 76 of which in cereals.
